        <!-- FAQ Section -->
        <section class="section faq-section">
            <h2 class="section-title">OM System OM-1 Mark II FAQ</h2>

            <div class="faq-container">
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <h3 class="faq-question">
                        Is Micro Four Thirds still relevant in 2026?
                        <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
                    </h3>
                    <div
                        class="faq-answer"
                        style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;"
                    >
                        <p>
                            Yes, for specific use cases. MFT excels where
                            portability, telephoto reach, and computational
                            features matter. The 2x crop factor provides
                            lightweight telephoto capabilities (a 300mm lens =
                            600mm equivalent). For landscape, wildlife, travel,
                            and adventure photography, MFT remains compelling.
                            However, for extreme low-light work, full-frame has
                            undeniable advantages.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <h3 class="faq-question">
                        How does image quality compare to full-frame?
                        <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
                    </h3>
                    <div
                        class="faq-answer"
                        style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;"
                    >
                        <p>
                            In good light (ISO 200-1600), image quality is
                            excellent and differences are minimal when viewing
                            at normal sizes. The smaller sensor shows
                            limitations above ISO 3200, with more visible noise
                            and less dynamic range than full-frame. However,
                            High-Res Shot mode (50MP) can match or exceed
                            full-frame resolution for static subjects. Choose
                            MFT for size/weight, choose full-frame for extreme
                            low-light.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <h3 class="faq-question">
                        What's the advantage of 120 fps burst?
                        <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
                    </h3>
                    <div
                        class="faq-answer"
                        style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;"
                    >
                        <p>
                            120 fps captures 120 images per second with
                            continuous AF/AE tracking‚Äîperfect for birds in
                            flight, fast-moving sports, and decisive moments.
                            Pro Capture mode adds a pre-record buffer (up to 70
                            frames before shutter press), virtually guaranteeing
                            you capture the peak action. Note: this uses
                            electronic shutter, so rolling shutter can be
                            visible with very fast motion.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <h3 class="faq-question">
                        How weather-sealed is the OM-1 Mark II really?
                        <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
                    </h3>
                    <div
                        class="faq-answer"
                        style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;"
                    >
                        <p>
                            Exceptionally. IP53 rating means it's tested against
                            dust and water jets from any angle. Freeze-proof to
                            -10¬∞C enables winter shooting. Combined with
                            weather-sealed PRO lenses, the system handles rain,
                            snow, sand, and harsh conditions where other cameras
                            shouldn't be used. Many professional nature
                            photographers choose OM System specifically for this
                            durability.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <h3 class="faq-question">
                        Who should buy the OM-1 Mark II?
                        <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
                    </h3>
                    <div
                        class="faq-answer"
                        style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;"
                    >
                        <p>
                            The OM-1 II is ideal for adventure photographers,
                            wildlife shooters who prioritize portability, travel
                            photographers, and anyone needing exceptional
                            weather sealing. It's perfect for hiking,
                            mountaineering, bird photography, and outdoor work
                            where carrying heavy full-frame systems isn't
                            practical. Skip it if extreme low-light performance
                            or maximum resolution are priorities.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Final Recommendation -->
        <section class="section">
            <div class="final-verdict">
                <h2>Final Recommendation</h2>
                <p>
                    The OM System OM-1 Mark II proves that sensor size isn't
                    everything. Through computational photography, exceptional
                    stabilization, and professional build quality, it delivers
                    capabilities that often exceed larger-sensor cameras in
                    specialized scenarios. For photographers who value
                    portability, weather resistance, and innovative features,
                    it's an outstanding choice.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <strong>Buy it if:</strong> You're an adventure photographer,
                    wildlife shooter prioritizing portability, or need exceptional
                    weather sealing. Perfect for hiking, travel, bird photography,
                    and outdoor work.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <strong>Skip it if:</strong> Extreme low-light performance or
                    maximum resolution are critical. Full-frame cameras offer advantages
                    for studio work, commercial photography, and very high ISO work.
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>
    </main>
